      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20
Look this all makes complete sense,=C2=A0obvious, intuitive, simple sense. =
If you are the richest person in the world, and annoying, and you constantl=
y play a computer game, and you get a lot of enjoyment and a sense of ident=
ity from that game and are maybe a little addicted, then at some point you =
might=C2=A0have some suggestions for improvements in the game. So you might=
 leave comments and email the company that makes the game saying =E2=80=9Ch=
ey you should try my ideas.=E2=80=9D And the company=C2=A0might ignore you =
(or respond politely but not move fast enough for your liking). It might oc=
cur to you: =E2=80=9CLook, I am the richest person in the world; how much c=
ould this game company possibly cost? I should just buy it and change the g=
ame however I want.=E2=80=9D Even if your complaints are quite minor, why s=
houldn=E2=80=99t you get to play exactly=C2=A0the game you want? Even if yo=
u have no complaints, why not own the game you love, just to make sure it c=
ontinues to be exactly what you want? The game is Twitter, the richest pers=
on in the world is Elon Musk,  and:Elon Musk has taken a 9.2% stake in Twit=
ter Inc. to become the platform=E2=80=99s biggest shareholder, a week after=
 hinting he might shake up the social media industry.Twitter shares surged =
about 26% in premarket trading after Musk=E2=80=99s purchase was revealed M=
onday in a regulatory filing. The stake is worth about $2.89 billion, based=
 on Friday=E2=80=99s market close.Musk, 50, polled his more than 80 million=
 followers on Twitter last month, asking them whether the company adheres t=
o the principles of free speech. After more than 70% said no, he asked whet=
her a new platform was needed and said he was giving serious thought to sta=
rting his own.=C2=A0I hope that if Elon Musk is going to do activism on Twi=
tter, it will not be for tedious=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cfree speech=E2=80=9D advocac=
y. I hope it is like:Twitter=E2=80=99s relatively new chief executive offic=
er, Parag Agrawal: Welcome, Mr. Musk. We=E2=80=99re so glad that you are ou=
r biggest shareholder. We have prepared a presentation showing how we are e=
xecuting on our strategy of being more technically nimble, building new pro=
ducts and growing revenue and active users. Here on slide 1 you can see=E2=
=80=94=C2=A0Elon Musk: Make the font bigger when I tweet.Agrawal: What?=C2=
=A0Musk: I am your biggest shareholder, I want the font on my tweets to be =
bigger than the font on everyone else=E2=80=99s tweets.Agrawal: That=E2=80=
=99s not really how we=E2=80=94Musk: And I want 290 characters. Again, just=
 for me.Agrawal: =E2=80=A6Musk: And it should play a little sound when I tw=
eet so everyone knows.Agrawal: I just feel like we want to make a good prod=
uct for all of our millions of users? I feel like that is going to improve =
profitability in the long run and, as our largest shareholder, you in parti=
cular stand to benefit from=E2=80=94Musk: Oh I don=E2=80=99t care even a li=
ttle bit about that, if your stock doubles that is rounding error on my net=
 worth, I just love tweeting and want to meddle a bit to optimize it for my=
 personal needs.I hope he demands a board seat. He=E2=80=99d be the first T=
witter user ever to join the board.[1] I hope he live-tweets the board meet=
ings.=C2=A0Actually the strange thing about Musk=E2=80=99s 9.2% stake is th=
at he disclosed it on Schedule 13G, which suggests that he is=C2=A0not=C2=
=A0planning to do activism or join the board.=C2=A0The ordinary way to disc=
lose an activist stake of more than 5% of a company is a Schedule 13D; you =
are eligible to use the shorter and less informative 13G only if you have =
=E2=80=9Cnot acquired the securities with any purpose, or with the effect, =
of changing or influencing the control of the issuer.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Right a=
way this strikes me as somewhat legally aggressive? Like, I am pretty sure =
that=C2=A0the Elon Musk Division of the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commis=
sion has already opened another inquiry into this filing. Elon Musk had acq=
uired at least some of his shares by March 14,[2] and on March 26 he was as=
king his followers =E2=80=9Cwhat should be done=E2=80=9D about Twitter=E2=
=80=99s =E2=80=9Cfailing to adhere to free speech principles.=E2=80=9D (A d=
ay earlier, he polled them about free speech and added, perhaps ominously, =
=E2=80=9Cthe consequences of this poll will be important.=E2=80=9D) Was he =
trying to =E2=80=9Cinfluence the control=E2=80=9D of Twitter, with those tw=
eets?=C2=A0I think in general if you went to a securities lawyer and said =
=E2=80=9CI am going to buy 9% of a public company and then make=C2=A0public=
 statements about how it should change its business, should=C2=A0I file a 1=
3D or 13G,=E2=80=9D the lawyer would say =E2=80=9Chmm that sounds like acti=
vism, which is traditionally on 13D.=E2=80=9D (Not legal advice!) But if yo=
u are Elon Musk you do not accept that sort of fuzzy reasoning. =E2=80=9CSh=
ow me where in these tweets I demand a change of control of Twitter,=E2=80=
=9D he presumably said to his harried securities lawyer, who by now  knows =
better than to argue.I guess nothing stops him from changing his mind and d=
oing activism later. Except that the SEC tends to look on that sort of thin=
g =E2=80=94=C2=A0building a =E2=80=9Cpassive=E2=80=9D position, filing a 13=
G, doing some public pressure campaigning, and later flipping to a 13D =E2=
=80=94 with suspicion. But the SEC looks on everything Musk does with suspi=
cion, and  he doesn=E2=80=99t care. All of the nuanced lore of activist dis=
closure=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t quite=C2=A0apply here.=C2=A0Still it is entire=
ly possible that Musk does=C2=A0not=C2=A0plan anything, that he=C2=A0isn=E2=
=80=99t=C2=A0looking to get a board seat or buy the whole company or even m=
ake the font bigger on his tweets. Perhaps this is just a passive financial=
 investment, as the 13G filing would imply if it were anyone but Musk. If s=
o it seems like a good one? As of 11 a.m. New York time today, Twitter was =
up about 25%, giving Musk a profit of more than $700 million on his Twitter=
 stake since he filed his 13G this morning. (It=E2=80=99s up about 50% sinc=
e March 14, though it=E2=80=99s unclear how many shares he owned by then.)=
=C2=A0Now, one move here would be to =E2=80=A6=C2=A0sell? We have talked a =
lot around here about the  Elon Markets Hypothesis, the idea that financial=
 assets are valuable not based on their cash flows but on their proximity t=
o Elon Musk. Few things are closer to Elon Musk than Twitter, but now it is=
, you know, 9.2% closer than it was before. Musk=E2=80=99s filing added $7.=
8 billion=C2=A0to the market value of Twitter, and 9.2% of that value accru=
es to him. If he were to sell his Twitter stock now =E2=80=94=C2=A0carefull=
y, you know, over the course of a few weeks or months[3] =E2=80=94=C2=A0the=
n he would have some time before he=E2=80=99d have to disclose that.[4] He =
bought his shares at the pre-Musk price and could presumably sell many of t=
hem at the post-Musk price for an easy nine-figure profit.This is true of D=
ogecoin and Bitcoin, too: Musk can buy them and tweet about buying them and=
 move the price up and then sell them at the new, higher, Musk-affected pri=
ce.=C2=A0We have  talked about it before, but entirely hypothetically, beca=
use=C2=A0it is impossible to imagine Elon Musk doing it. Elon Musk is not d=
oing a pump and dump! Elon Musk is not interested in a quick and easy nine-=
figure profit, that is absurd. Elon Musk did not buy 9.2% of Twitter to=C2=
=A0make money. He already has all the money, and Twitter has kind of a mixe=
d record of making money for its public shareholders. He bought 9.2% of Twi=
tter because he=C2=A0has money, and wants to spend some of it on=C2=A0being=
 more annoying on Twitter. I cannot tell you exactly how =E2=80=94=C2=A0pre=
sumably not through traditional activism, proxy fights, etc., though who kn=
ows really =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I bet we=E2=80=99ll=C2=A0find out.For a while=
 there was a broad consensus about what public companies were for. The goal=
 of a public company, all the sophisticated people agreed, was to make as m=
uch money as possible for its shareholders. Sometimes managers got distract=
ed from this goal, and then there was shareholder activism to get them back=
 in line. =E2=80=9CWe want to replace management with other managers who wi=
ll make more money for shareholders,=E2=80=9D an activist would say, and if=
 other shareholders agreed with her plans then she=E2=80=99d win a proxy fi=
ght and replace the managers and the system would move toward the perfect g=
oal of maximizing profits.When I started in corporate law and finance, this=
 consensus had been dominant for decades and felt very, very stable. In 202=
2 it seems like a weird historical blip, a few decades (1980 to 2010?) when=
 everyone fell into a radically oversimplified understanding of what compan=
ies are. Now everyone =E2=80=94=C2=A0even big-company CEOs =E2=80=94=C2=A0t=
alks about =E2=80=9Cstakeholder capitalism,=E2=80=9D the idea that companie=
s don=E2=80=99t just answer to shareholders but have to optimize for lots o=
f different constituencies that want different things. And even shareholder=
s don=E2=80=99t monolithically want profit maximization: Many of them care =
about environmental, social and governance issues, and a company has to wei=
gh those issues against profits just to keep the shareholders happy. And  s=
hareholder activism now can serve  ESG purposes: If you pollute too much, t=
he shareholders might throw you out.But whereas the old consensus said that=
 companies should maximize one thing, and identified what that thing was, t=
he new theories do not. Now companies are for, you know, whatever someone w=
ith a lot of money wants them to be for. This is I think largely what they =
were for=C2=A0before=C2=A0the 1980s profit-maximizing consensus, too. This =
is not a particularly normative or predictive model, but it is a simple one=
.You can have various sophisticated systematic theories of ESG, and if you =
are an institutional investor you probably should. But then there is Carl I=
cahn, a billionaire longtime activist investor who has gotten very interest=
ed in one animal-welfare issue and has plans to run proxy fights at  McDona=
ld=E2=80=99s Corp. and Kroger Co. to make them treat pigs better. Presumabl=
y to win a proxy fight he will need to appeal to other investors by making =
broad arguments about ESG (=E2=80=9Cvote for me, if you claim to be a good =
ESG fund=E2=80=9D) and even about profit maximization (=E2=80=9Ctreating pi=
gs humanely is better for business in the long run=E2=80=9D). But if you ar=
e an executive at those companies, you might feel a little bit like what is=
 happening here is =E2=80=9Cthis rich guy=E2=80=99s hobby is making me chan=
ge how I run my business.=E2=80=9D Humane treatment of pigs was not at the =
top of your agenda, and it was not at the top of your biggest institutional=
 shareholders=E2=80=99 agendas. But it is at the top of Carl Icahn=E2=80=99=
s agenda, for essentially idiosyncratic personal reasons, and now companies=
 have to listen to him because he has a lot of money and is very persistent=
 and cares a lot.=C2=A0Elon Musk has even more money and is even more persi=
stent and nobody has ever cared more about anything than he cares about twe=
eting. If he wants to change Twitter, he might have to gesture in the direc=
tion of ESG (=E2=80=9CGiven that Twitter serves as the de facto public town=
 square, failing to adhere to free speech principles fundamentally undermin=
es democracy=E2=80=9D) or profitability to get other shareholders to suppor=
t him. Or he could just buy more stock and tell Twitter what to do.=C2=A0=
=C2=A0
