      Sure also GameStop
   =20
 =20
Last Thursday after the close, GameStop Corp. announced that it is planning=
 a=C2=A0stock split, missing April Fool=E2=80=99s Day by hours. The stock o=
pened up almost 14% on Friday, though it lost those gains and closed down o=
n the day. We  talked last week about stock splits, with the gist of it bei=
ng =E2=80=9Cstock splits are good for meme stocks,=E2=80=9D and several sto=
cks with very high prices and name recognition have split in recent years. =
Is GameStop basically in the same category as Tesla, Alphabet Inc. and Amaz=
on.com Inc.? Sure why not.Incidentally the phrase =E2=80=9Cstock dividend=
=E2=80=9D has sort of bubbled up in popular awareness recently so let=E2=80=
=99s do a quick explainer. Under Delaware corporate law (the law that appli=
es to GameStop and Tesla and most other big U.S. public companies), there i=
s a standard way to do a stock split. Section 242(a)(3) of the Delaware Gen=
eral Corporation Law allows a company to amend its corporate charter =E2=80=
=9Cto increase or decrease its authorized capital stock ...=C2=A0by subdivi=
ding or combining the outstanding shares of any class or series of a class =
of shares into a greater or lesser number of outstanding shares." So you ca=
n turn every share into two shares, or 10 shares, or turn every two shares =
into one share, or seven into three, or whatever.=C2=A0This requires a shar=
eholder vote, though, which is a pain. At some point lawyers realized that =
there is a different provision of the law =E2=80=94=C2=A0section 173 =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0that allows companies to pay dividends =E2=80=9Cin shares of the c=
orporation=E2=80=99s capital stock,=E2=80=9D without a shareholder vote. So=
 instead of saying =E2=80=9Ceach share of stock splits into two shares,=E2=
=80=9D which requires a shareholder=C2=A0vote, you can say =E2=80=9Ceach sh=
are of stock will receive a dividend of one share of stock,=E2=80=9D which =
has exactly the same effect but does not require a vote. So that=E2=80=99s =
the normal way to do a forward=C2=A0stock split in modern public companies.=
 (A reverse stock split =E2=80=94=C2=A0every 10 shares become one share =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0still requires section 242 and a vote.)=C2=A0GameStop and Tesla=
 can=E2=80=99t really do a stock-split-by-dividend, though, because they do=
n=E2=80=99t have enough authorized shares. So they have both announced that=
 they will ask their shareholders to vote to amend their charters to author=
ize more shares, and=C2=A0then=C2=A0they will do a stock-split-by-dividend.=
 (This is presumably a bit tidier than asking the shareholders to vote on a=
 stock-split-by-section-242 in part because it gives the board a bit more f=
lexibility to change its mind and in part because it lets you authorize=C2=
=A0some extra shares for other purposes.) But there is nothing unusual abou=
t the fact that they=E2=80=99re doing the stock split this way; it=E2=80=99=
s just unusual that they had to mention it.
