   =20
      Meanwhile in Paulsboro
   =20
 =20
Honestly it has been a wild few days=C2=A0for Money-Stuff-ish financial new=
s stories. Here=E2=80=99s this:Hometown International =E2=80=94 that odd, p=
ublicly traded company with a market capitalization of more than $100 milli=
on despite owning just one small New Jersey deli =E2=80=94 has announced pl=
ans to merge with Makamer, a private bioplastics start-up firm.The money-lo=
sing Your Hometown Deli in Paulsboro, N.J., which is owned by Hometown Inte=
rnational, will not be operated by the company that will result from the me=
rger with the Los Angeles-based Makamer.But a woman who answered the phone =
at the deli on Friday said, =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re still going to be open=
=E2=80=9D after the merger is completed.We  talked a  lot about  the deli b=
ack  in 2021, and I characterized it as =E2=80=9Ca weird SPAC,=E2=80=9D a s=
hell company that its backers were planning to use to merge with a private =
(or foreign) company to take it public without the usual procedures of an i=
nitial public offering. Apparently it found a target. The deli is not=C2=A0=
a true shell company in that it actually runs a deli, but I suppose it=E2=
=80=99s not that hard to get rid of the deli.=C2=A0Here is the announcement=
 of the merger. Here is the merger agreement, which does say that =E2=80=9C=
incoming management will continue to evaluate and determine the viability o=
f the Parent=E2=80=99s existing delicatessen business currently operated th=
rough its subsidiary Your Hometown Deli.=E2=80=9D I do not want to know abo=
ut the potential synergies between bioplastics and the deli.
