emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked last week=
</a> about stock splits, with the gist of it being =E2=80=9Cstock splits ar=
e good for meme stocks,=E2=80=9D and several stocks with very high prices a=
nd name recognition have split in recent years. Is GameStop basically in th=
e same category as Tesla, Alphabet Inc. and Amazon.com Inc.? Sure why not.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Incidentally the phrase =E2=80=9Cstock divi=
dend=E2=80=9D has sort of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/27253239.266604/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9tYXR0X2xldmluZS9zdGF0dXM=
vMTUwODYwMjUzMjcyNTIwMjk1NA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4198c11b" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">bubb=
led up</a> in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2725=
3239.266604/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9hYV9sZWhtYW5uL3N0YXR1cy8xNTA5ODkzNTU=
0MjM1MDgwNzA4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB660520b2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">popular awareness<=
/a> recently so let=E2=80=99s do a quick explainer. Under Delaware corporat=
e law (the law that applies to GameStop and Tesla and most other big U.S. p=
ublic companies), there is a standard way to do a stock split. <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27253239.266604/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZW=
xjb2RlLmRlbGF3YXJlLmdvdi90aXRsZTgvYzAwMS9zYzA4L2luZGV4Lmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB7c8faa7e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">Section 242(a)(3)</a> of the Delaware General=
 Corporation Law allows a company to amend its corporate charter =E2=80=9Ct=
o increase or decrease its authorized capital stock ...=C2=A0by subdividing=
 or combining the outstanding shares of any class or series of a class of s=
hares into a greater or lesser number of outstanding shares." So you can tu=
rn every share into two shares, or 10 shares, or turn every two shares into=
 one share, or seven into three, or whatever.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">This requires a shareholder vote, though, which is a pain. At some=
 point lawyers realized that there is a different provision of the law =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/272532=
39.266604/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZWxjb2RlLmRlbGF3YXJlLmdvdi90aXRsZTgvYzAwMS9zYzA1L2luZ=
GV4Lmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2abac733" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">section 173</a> =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0that allows companies to pay dividends =E2=80=9Cin shares of th=
e corporation=E2=80=99s capital stock,=E2=80=9D without a shareholder vote.=
 So instead of saying =E2=80=9Ceach share of stock splits into two shares,=
=E2=80=9D which requires a shareholder=C2=A0vote, you can say =E2=80=9Ceach=
 share of stock will receive a dividend of one share of stock,=E2=80=9D whi=
ch has exactly the same effect but does not require a vote. So that=E2=80=
=99s the normal way to do a forward=C2=A0stock split in modern public compa=
nies. (A reverse stock split =E2=80=94=C2=A0every 10 shares become one shar=
e =E2=80=94=C2=A0still requires section 242 and a vote.)=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">GameStop and Tesla can=E2=80=99t really do a stock-spl=
it-by-dividend, though, because they don=E2=80=99t have enough authorized s=
hares. So they have both announced that they will ask their shareholders to=
 vote to amend their charters to authorize more shares, and=C2=A0<em>then=
=C2=A0</em>they will do a stock-split-by-dividend. (This is presumably a bi=
t tidier than asking the shareholders to vote on a stock-split-by-section-2=
42 in part because it gives the board a bit more flexibility to change its =
mind and in part because it lets you authorize=C2=A0some extra shares for o=
ther purposes.) But there is nothing unusual about the fact that they=E2=80=
